> Hello everybody,
 
Howdy!

> sorry for the stupid question, but I\'m new both to Traveller and this 
> list. I just skimmed over the rules for Briliant Lances and Fire, 
> Fusion and Steel, and there is one thing I don\'t  understand:
> why are all the ship-to-ship missiles nuclear-powered laser warheads? 
> Why doesn\'t anyone use simple nuclear warheads instead?

They decided apriori that nothing else could makle a fire solution, then
later
that while a fire solution for kinetic energy or nuke missiles *was*
possible,
they would *all* be shot down before they reached their targets since they
would be moving in a perfectly predicible way (amazingly, even totally
*unarmed*
ships can do this!).
 
> In Brilliant Lances, the missiles have to reach the hex the target is 
> located in, so there is no advantage (in game terms) in firing a 
> laser from some (relatively close) distance, as opposed to moving 
> near the target and detonating a warhead (like better survivability 
> of the missile due to lesser likelihood of being shot down. Doesn\'t 
> apply if you have to reach the target\'s hex).
> 
Well, while the det-laser weapons should have a better shot at hitting, there
is no rational reason why you couldn\'t get a nuke close enough to, well, nuke
the other guy (if you can board, why can\'t you nuke?).  On the other hand, at
BL/BR velocities a nuke is redundant compared to the KE of the empty
missile----
not to mention the fact that dampers will stop a nuke.

> Am I missing something? Do I misinterpret a rule? Any hints?
> 
That\'s the way the rules are.  You\'ll have to use a house-rule (I *just*
posted
BR kinetic energy missile rules).

> Well, excuse my ignorance, and thanks a lot for any clues...

You\'re no more ignorant than the rest of us when it comes to the missile
rules 
:-)

