    'topic' => ' Barbettes',
    'body' => '
"Christopher Weuve" <caw@intercon.com> writes:

 ----
HA281PMR01@ntu.ac.uk (Lynx) said:
> A barbette is essentially a larger turret capable of holding more
> or larger weapons. Historically, i can only think of the Barbette
> occuring in aircraft. Many WWII aircraft mounted single/double machine
> gun turrets. The Northrop Black Widow had a remotely controlled
> barbette mounting four weapons. I can\'t remember if the weapons
> were standard machine guns, .50cal Brownings, 20mm cannon etc.

Webster\'s defines a [naval] barbette as "the armored structure around a gun
platform on a warship".
 ----

Yep, reader\'s of my previous post on this subject:

                            TRAVELLER Digest 368
  2) Re: Fire Fusion and Steel
        by "Upton, Django" <DUpton@vtrnntov.telecom.com.au>

will see that I agree with this definition.

 ----
Historically barbettes were limited traverse weapon
mounts located on the sides of ships.
 ----

I think you\'re getting confused with CASEMATE mounts.
Most barbette mounts are not limited in traverse except by the presence of 
the ships superstructure.

 ----
The barbette itself does not move --
rather, it functioned as an armored blister for the weapon itself.  Pre-
dreadnought battleships often had barbettes on the sides of the ship in
addition to turrets on top -- Dewey\'s flagship at the Battle of Manilla Bay
(USS Olympia?) has this configuration.
 ----

A typical Pre-dreadnought battle ship has 2 turrets (one fore and one aft ) 
each with 2 12 inch guns; a secondary armament of ~12 6 inch guns would be 
mounted in casemates along the sides of the ship. The ship would have no 
Barbette mounts at all!
I don\'t know about the particular ship you mention ( which may well have had 
barbettes for all I know... but I doubt it ) but barbettes were NOT common 
on Pre-dreadnought Battleships and Cruisers.

In the 20th century barbette mounts have mainly been used for AA guns,
examples being the single mount 5 inch guns on old battleships used in WWII 
and the quad 40mm mounts used extensively on many warship types in WWII.

The remotely controlled weapons mount on the Black Widow was a *turret*, not
a barbette.
 ----

The remote turret on the P61 may have been called a barbette because of its 
flat shape compared with the round turrets used on other aircraft at the 
time.

Django.
'
